A '''diagonal matrix''', <math>A</math>, is a square matrix in which the entries outside of the main diagonal are zero. The '''main diagonal''' of a square matrix consists of the entries which run from the top left corner to the bottom right corner.
In the example below the main diagonal are <math>a_{11}, a_{22}, ..., a_{nn}\!</math> :<math> \quad A=\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & 0 & \cdots & 0 \\ 0 & a_{22} & \cdots & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & \cdots & a_{nn}\end{bmatrix}</math>
